    {
      "id": "47f97c175a03139ef8c112e86ae995eaf28c1c33",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-12-03 11:04:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 7:\n\nThis build and the next one is failing on RHEL6 with:\n\n WARNING: lustre-2.5.52/lustre/ptlrpc/gss/ptlrpc_gss.o(.init.text+0x2f5):\n   Section mismatch in reference from the function gss_init_lproc()\n   to the function .exit.text:gss_exit_lproc()\n The function __init gss_init_lproc() references\n a function __exit gss_exit_lproc().\n This is often seen when error handling in the init function\n uses functionality in the exit path.\n The fix is often to remove the __exit annotation of\n gss_exit_lproc() so it may be used outside an exit section.\n\nand many similar errors.  I've cancelled the rest of the patches in this series.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 7
    },
    {
      "id": "3010b49eaf9833c4acccf629f0321d1f0bd23790",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2013-12-03 16:24:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 7:\n\nI see what the problem is. My use of gss_exit_lproc to do cleanup in gss_init_lproc on failure is breaking the build due to the __exit being used with gss_exit_lproc. The other error messages already exist before this patch but my final addition tipped the build system over the edge. I can submit a new patch which removes the __exit to see if it passes building but the other errors need to be addressed in another patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 7
    },
